@Fact Boy

@Steve L explain TCS to this guy

It's ironic, your explanation proves that the clue is valid. Biden and Macron are both heads of state. The fact that they both attend NATOSUMMIT periodically makes the clue valid with no further debate

@CCNY 

I'm repeating myself, but....I missed several MORE fun clues, I see from your post.  

Ah, well.

@Lewis

This comment really increased my appreciation for the puzzle. 

And just to save anyone else a lookup, a “semordnilap” is a word that spells another word when read in reverse. It’s actually “palindromes” backwards.

@Nancy 
Do you know about about Easy Mode Friday puzzles? That's where the Times now presents the same Friday puzzle with some of the clues rewritten to make the puzzle easier to solve.
One has to sign up to get it by email and you may have to have a Games subscription to sign up.  (I forget.) Anyway, I sometimes wonder if knowing that Friday puzzles get that treatment affects constructors in some way.

@Kate 
I went out at 5:50 a.m. and it was still a bit late to enjoy "the 'cool' of the morning."  

A female mallard had been nesting in 'landscape grasses' near the street over past weeks, and was pacing nervously as I worked.  Later I checked the nest--empty now--and saw her down the street with one (possibly two) babies...of six eggs incubated.  Life is tough.

@PhiloTM yes! I read it on Safari iOS and have seen the same exact ad, four or five times per page, every day for a year. For some tacky, cheap walking shoes I wouldn’t be caught dead in. I have repeatedly marked it irrelevant, not interested, “have seen this ad multiple times”, all to no avail. I edited my Google Search history to modify the ads I see and learned I did search for running shoes once in 2017. Deleted that. Still get the same ad, and no others. 

Anyone else getting the same shoe ad that begins with V? Wonder if it’s NYT making that choice and not Google Ads. 

If I use DuckDuckGo, I see no ads. I need to switch my default browser one of these days.

@Emilie 

I'm a nerd, too.  A proud nerd.

Nerds of the world, unite!

@Joya 

I think the tracking of streaks was a genius move on the part of the NYT. 

It's a strangely powerful way to keep people coming back.

@Barry Ancona 

I second that (e)motion.




I would have appreciated this more if I didn't feel cheated by the lack of an end of week workout.
